{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622870"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:06:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:06:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16826"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16826"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.11,0.24,0.21,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76653"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9517"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62150"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22483"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76653"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBlood supply to the spinal cord is maintained through a complex network of vessels entering at multiple vertebral levels. These segmental vessels originate from different arterial sources depending on the spinal region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following arteries contributes segmental branches to supply the spinal cord?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vertebral arteries","Radicular arteries","Anterior spinal artery","Posterior spinal arteries","Internal carotid arteries"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evertebral arteries\u003C/strong\u003E provide important segmental branches that supply the cervical region of the spinal cord. Additional segmental contributions come from ascending cervical, deep cervical, posterior intercostal, lumbar and lateral sacral arteries at their respective levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding why the other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadicular arteries\u003C/strong\u003E are themselves branches that arise from segmental vessels rather than being a source\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior spinal artery\u003C/strong\u003E is a longitudinal vessel formed by branches from vertebral arteries - it receives blood from segmental vessels but does not give rise to them\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior spinal arteries\u003C/strong\u003E are also longitudinal channels that receive rather than provide segmental supply\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal carotid arteries\u003C/strong\u003E supply intracranial structures but do not contribute to spinal cord blood supply\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis segmental pattern ensures reliable blood supply along the entire length of the spinal cord through multiple feeding vessels entering at different levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Segmental arteries that supply the spinal cord originate from different sources at each vertebral level.","The vertebral arteries provide segmental branches to supply the cervical spinal cord.","Multiple regional arteries contribute to spinal cord blood supply through segmental branches."],"references":["Hasan S, Arain A. Neuroanatomy, Spinal Cord Arteries. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539889/","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62150"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16826"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62150"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T20:16:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T20:17:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9517"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76653"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data